:::summary
Raffaello Sanzio da Urbino (1483–1520), universally known as Raphael, was one of the three supreme masters of the Italian High Renaissance — alongside [Leonardo da Vinci](article.html?id=da-vinci) and [Michelangelo](article.html?id=michelangelo) — celebrated for the serene beauty, compositional clarity, and graceful idealism of his paintings and frescoes. His *School of Athens* — a vast fresco depicting the great philosophers of antiquity gathered in a grand classical hall — is one of the defining images of Western intellectual culture. Raphael died at 37, leaving a body of work that established the standard of classical beauty and harmonious composition for European painting for centuries.
:::

